{
  "doc_id": "36035",
  "text": "A number of drugs, originally approved for a different action, were later found to enhance K ir channel function; e.g., K ir 1.1 (Pregabaline) and K ir 2.3 (Tenidap; [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Furthermore, supporting K ir 3 channel [CITATION_3] and K ir 2 channel [CITATION_4] ) function in vivo is effective against seizures of certain epilepsy models (Table 2) . Finally, K 2P 2.1 upregulation via adenoviral gene therapy reduces EEG seizures in the sPilo model [CITATION_5] . Hence, leak K channels could be an attractive AED target. Again, especially K ir 2.1-2.4 and K 2P 2.1 leak channels, which are endogenously upregulated in DG GCs during epileptic hyperexcitability, appear to be good candidates . Although enhancing K channel function is a plausible antiepileptic strategy, there are drawbacks. For example, too much silencing via K channels can also be detrimental [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] . Furthermore, as discussed for the thalamus, de-inactivation of Na v and Ca v channels necessary for AP activation results in the counterintuitive effect that enhancing K currents can increase seizure susceptibility. One example is the big conductance, Caactivated K (BK) channel. These channels contribute to the fast AHP, enabling high AP frequencies. Consequently, enhancing BK currents has proepileptic effects [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] [CITATION_11] . If in turn the fast AHP is impaired in interneurons, e.g., via loss of K v 3.2 channels, seizures become more likely [CITATION_12] . Hence, the usability of K channel enhancing AEDs has to be carefully evaluated.",
